77.description: Unique identity of any object (commit, tree, blob, tag).

78.description: Parse a hex formatted object id into a git_oid.

79.description: Copy an already raw oid into a git_oid structure.

80.name: git_oid_fmt
80.description: Format a git_oid into a hex string.

81.name: git_oid_pathfmt
81.description:
Format a git_oid into a loose-object path string.
 

 The resulting string is "aa/...", where "aa" is the first two
 hex digitis of the oid and "..." is the remaining 38 digits.

82.name: git_oid_allocfmt
82.description: Format a gid_oid into a newly allocated c-string.

83.name: git_oid_to_string
83.description:
Format a git_oid into a buffer as a hex format c-string.
 

 If the buffer is smaller than GIT_OID_HEXSZ+1, then the resulting
 oid c-string will be truncated to n-1 characters. If there are
 any input parameter errors (out == NULL, n == 0, oid == NULL),
 then a pointer to an empty string is returned, so that the return
 value can always be printed.

84.name: git_oid_cpy
84.description: Copy an oid from one structure to another.

96.name: GIT_SORT_NONE
96.description: Sort the repository contents in no particular ordering; this sorting is arbitrary, implementation-specific and subject to change at any time. This is the default sorting for new walkers.

97.name: GIT_SORT_TOPOLOGICAL
97.description: Sort the repository contents in topological order (parents before children); this sorting mode can be combined with time sorting.

98.name: GIT_SORT_TIME
98.description: Sort the repository contents by commit time; this sorting mode can be combined with topological sorting.

99.name: GIT_SORT_REVERSE
99.description: Iterate through the repository contents in reverse order; this sorting mode can be combined with any of the above.
